body:
The following will loop indefinitely if canonicalized. Run with `circt-opt -canonicalize Foo.mlir`:

``` mlir
firrtl.circuit "Foo" {
  firrtl.module private @Bar(
    in %clk: !firrtl.clock,
    in %rst: !firrtl.asyncreset
  ) {
    %c0_ui1 = firrtl.constant 0 : !firrtl.const.uint<1>
    %c0_ui4 = firrtl.constant 0 : !firrtl.const.uint<4>
    %reg = firrtl.regreset %clk, %rst, %c0_ui4 : !firrtl.clock, !firrtl.asyncreset, !firrtl.const.uint<4>, !firrtl.uint<4>
    %0 = firrtl.bits %reg 0 to 0 : (!firrtl.uint<4>) -> !firrtl.uint<1>
    %1 = firrtl.eq %c0_ui1, %c0_ui1 : (!firrtl.const.uint<1>, !firrtl.const.uint<1>) -> !firrtl.const.uint<1>
    %2 = firrtl.and %1, %0 : (!firrtl.const.uint<1>, !firrtl.uint<1>) -> !firrtl.uint<1>
    firrtl.when %2 : !firrtl.uint<1> {
    }
  }
  firrtl.extmodule @Foo()
}
```

For background, I've been seeing issues with `circt-reduce` for some time where canonicalization will get stuck and I need to exclude it to make forward progress. Eventually, I will reenable it once the reduction has proceeded far enough.
